The Deputy Secretary General, United Nations (UN), Amina Mohammed, said Nigeria is moving in the right direction economically but very slow. She stated this during a visit to the Minister of Industry, Trade and Investment Adeniyi Adebayo in Abuja, lamenting that the challenge in Nigeria are huge with large population yet described the economy as great with good opportunities. According to her, after travelling by train and through various roads in the northern parts of Nigeria, she discovered that the roads were motorable, although there were ongoing repairs on some of them. She added that the country is diverse, ethnicity, religious backgrounds and in opportunities, which are its strengths, not weaknesses. It is time the narrative for Nigeria change to one that is very much the reality. Speaking on her trips across parts of Nigeria, she said: “What I saw along the way is really a country that is growing, that is moving in the right direction both economically. Is it fast enough? No. Is it in the right direction? Yes it is.” “And the challenges still remain with security, our social cohesion and social contract between government and the people. But I know that people are working on these issues.” She said the UN recognised the reforms in Nigeria and other nations, adding that the common global agenda was the Sustainable Development Goals. Otunba Adeniyi assured Mrs. Mohommed that the government is working hard to make Nigeria the entrepreneurial hub of Africa. stating that before the end of the first quarter of 2021, there should be a document on the government’s investment policies, as efforts were on to take Nigeria out of its mono-economy.